 with his healthcare provider. It is also important for him to follow the instructions of his healthcare provider and take his medication as prescribed."}, {"label": 0, "content": "HiLyme's disease is a bacterial infection , hence antibiotics are given for the treatment.Lyme disease is best treated in the early stages. Early treatment is a simple 14 to 21 day course of oral antibiotics. This can eliminate all traces of infection. Medications used to treat Lyme disease are:  1.  doxycycline for adults and children older than 8 years old   2.  cefuroxime and amoxicillin for adults, younger children, and women who are nursing or breast-feedingHope this information was of help.Thank you."}, {"label": 1, "content": "Lyme disease is a bacterial infection caused by the Borrelia bacteria. It is transmitted to humans through the bite of infected ticks. Symptoms of Lyme disease can include fever, chills, headache, fatigue, muscle and joint aches, and a characteristic skin rash called erythema migrans. If left untreated, the infection can spread to the joints, heart, and nervous system, leading to more severe symptoms.\n\nThe treatment for Lyme disease typically involves the use of antibiotics. The specific antibiotic and duration of treatment will depend on the stage of the infection and the severity of the symptoms. In early stage infections, a course of oral antibiotics may be sufficient. In more severe cases or in later stages of the infection, intravenous antibiotics may be necessary.\n\nIt is important to seek medical treatment as soon as possible if you suspect that you have been infected with Lyme disease. Early treatment can help to prevent the infection from spreading and can help to prevent more severe symptoms from developing.\n\nAs for the range for EBV tests, the specific range can vary depending on the type of test being used and the laboratory that is conducting the test. It is important to discuss the results of any laboratory tests with a healthcare provider, who can interpret the results and determine the appropriate course of treatment."}, {"label": 0, "content": "A bilirubin of .3  is of no concern . There is fluctuation as you suggested, of the blood tests. I don't think your liver shows signs of trouble at this time. Continue to have blood checked for enzyme elevation(ast, alt) or presence of virus."}, {"label": 1, "content": "Elevated bilirubin levels can be caused by a variety of factors, including liver disease. It is possible that your liver is beginning to fail, but it is also possible that other factors may be contributing to the fluctuation in your bilirubin levels. Some possible causes of elevated bilirubin include:\n\nLiver disease: Elevated bilirubin can be a sign of liver damage or disease, such as hepatitis or cirrhosis.\n\nBlockage of the bile ducts: If the bile ducts that carry bile from the liver to the small intestine are blocked, bilirubin can build up in the body, leading to elevated levels.\n\nHemolysis: Hemolysis is the breakdown of red blood cells. When red blood cells break down, they release bilirubin into the bloodstream, which can lead to elevated bilirubin levels.\n\nMedications: Some medications, such as certain antibiotics and anti-seizure medications, can increase bilirubin levels.\n\nIt is important to discuss your elevated bilirubin levels with your healthcare provider to determine the cause and appropriate treatment. Your healthcare provider may recommend further testing, such as liver function tests or imaging studies, to help determine the cause of your elevated bilirubin."}, {"label": 0, "content": "Hello and welcome to \u2018Ask A Doctor\u2019 service. I have reviewed your query and here is my advice. You should get her vitamin B 12 levels checked too.It's deficiency may lead to memory impairment. Hope I have answered your query. Let me know if I can assist you further."}, {"label": 1, "content": "It is possible that the delay in regaining memory despite taking Levothyroxine may 