nline/internal-medicine-physician"}, {"label": 1, "content": "Q. How to correct bedwetting of a 9 year old?Hi doctor,My child, who is 9 years old, has bedwetting problem. Please suggest me.\nBedwetting, also known as enuresis, is a common problem among children, and it is usually not a cause for concern. Most children outgrow bedwetting on their own, and treatment is usually not necessary. However, if your child's bedwetting is causing distress or problems, there are several things you can try to help your child stop wetting the bed:\n\nEncourage your child to go to the bathroom before bedtime and make sure they empty their bladder completely.\n\nConsider using an alarm system to wake your child up when they start to wet the bed. These alarms can be purchased online or at a medical supply store.\n\nTry to reduce your child's fluid intake in the evening, particularly caffeine-containing drinks like soda and chocolate.\n\nConsider using a bedwetting product, such as a moisture-absorbing mattress pad or a bedwetting alarm that attaches to your child's clothing.\n\nTalk to your child's doctor about whether medication might be helpful in managing the bedwetting.\n\nIt's important to be patient and understanding with your child as they learn to control their bladder. Bedwetting can be a frustrating and embarrassing problem, but with your support and encouragement, your child can overcome it."}, {"label": 0, "content": "Hi,It seems that you might be having enlarged tender axillary lymph  nodes giving this problem.This shows that there might be having some infection in surrounding area like hands, some infection following shaving the part.consult your doctor and get examined and go for treatment of infection if present.Ok and take care."}, {"label": 1, "content": "Swollen lymph nodes in the armpit can be a sign of an underlying health issue. Lymph nodes are small, bean-shaped glands that are part of the immune system. They help to filter out bacteria, viruses, and other foreign substances that may cause infection or disease. When lymph nodes become swollen, it can be a sign that the body is fighting off an infection or other type of inflammation.\n\nThere are many possible causes of swollen lymph nodes in the armpit, including infections such as the common cold, flu, or strep throat; other conditions such as allergies, autoimmune disorders, and cancer; and injuries or surgical procedures.\n\nIf you have swollen lymph nodes in your armpit that are tender to the touch and have been present for more than a few days, it is important to speak with a healthcare provider. They can perform a physical examination and may order additional tests to determine the cause of the swelling.\n\nIt is not always easy to tell when a lump in the armpit is something to be concerned about. If you notice a new lump or swelling in your armpit that is accompanied by other symptoms such as fever, weight loss, or difficulty swallowing, it is important to speak with a healthcare provider. They can help you determine whether the lump is likely to be a cause for concern and recommend appropriate treatment."}, {"label": 0, "content": "not to worry much as this is benign condition like a bursa or a hematoma!if really worries you can go for an FNAC test for confirmationall the best!"}, {"label": 1, "content": "It is not possible for me to diagnose the cause of a lump above your knee without examining you in person and obtaining a thorough medical history. It is important that you see a healthcare provider for a proper evaluation and diagnosis.\n\nThere are many potential causes of a lump above the knee, some of which may be benign (non-cancerous) and others that may be more serious. Possible causes of a lump above the knee include:\n\nBursitis: This is inflammation of a bursa, which are small fluid-filled sacs that act as cushions between bones and soft tissues. Bursitis can cause a painful lump to develop above the knee.\n\nCellulitis: This is a bacterial infection o