rea clean and avoiding hard or crunchy foods that may irritate the bumps or cause further swelling."}, {"label": 0, "content": "Dear Gogku,                   As you have said your child is taking EPILEX CHRONO200, EPTOIN 100.Now he is 5 yr old and still not able to speak. So I feel you should perform an IQ assesment. For his other behavioral problem he may need some low dose Risperidon, which will help him severly.Dont waste time just go for an IQ, he may need some special attention and care. You may consult an PSYCHAITRIST , he will guide you in this matter."}, {"label": 1, "content": "It's concerning that your child is experiencing difficulty speaking and is hyperactive. It's important to discuss any changes in your child's behavior or development with their doctor. It's also important to make sure that the medications your child is taking are appropriate and are not causing any negative side effects. It's generally recommended that children with seizure disorders be under the care of a pediatric neurologist or epilepsy specialist.\n\nIt's also important to carefully follow the dosing instructions for any medications that your child is taking. If you have concerns about the medications or their side effects, it's important to discuss them with your child's doctor. They may be able to adjust the dosage or try a different medication to see if it is more effective for your child.\n\nAdditionally, it may be helpful to work with a speech therapist or other specialists to help your child improve their communication skills. It's also important to provide a supportive and nurturing environment for your child, as this can help with their overall development and well-being."}, {"label": 0, "content": "Hi, If the doctors who examined her told you not to worry means she is in the right growth velocity. No need to worry. growth will occur up to 18 years so no need to worry. You can give protein-rich food to help her grow. Hope I have answered your query. Let me know if I can assist you further. Regards,Dr. Rajmohan, Pediatrician"}, {"label": 1, "content": "It is normal for children to grow at different rates, and it is not uncommon for children to have periods of faster or slower growth. It is important to remember that genetics play a significant role in a child's height, so it is possible that your daughter's height is within the normal range for her genetic potential.\n\nIt is not advisable to try to increase your child's height through medical intervention or supplements, as this can have negative effects on their overall health and development. Children should be allowed to grow at their own natural pace, and it is important to focus on providing a healthy diet and lifestyle to support their growth and development.\n\nIf you have concerns about your child's growth, it is important to speak with a healthcare professional. They can assess your child's growth and development and provide guidance on how to support their health and well-being."}, {"label": 0, "content": "HiYou can consume both the tablets at different time as you are already consuming.Take the tablets after food.Adequate hydration and healthy nutritious diet is also essential.Hope that was helpful.Let me know if i can assist you further.RegardsDr.Saranya RamadossGeneral and Family Health Physician"}, {"label": 1, "content": "It is generally not recommended to take multiple supplements or medications at the same time unless directed to do so by a healthcare provider. Mixing different supplements or medications can potentially lead to harmful interactions or unintended side effects.\n\nFollihair and Revital are both dietary supplements that contain a variety of vitamins, minerals, and other nutrients. It is important to be aware of the potential for overlap in the ingredients of these supplements and to consider the total daily intake of these nutrients from all sources, including food, other supplements, and medications.\n\nBefore taking any supplement or medication, it is always a good idea to consult with a healthcare provider to ensure that it is appropriate for you and to discuss any potential risks or interactions. Your healthcare provider will be able to advise you on the safe and appropriate use of these products based on your specific needs and medical history."}, {"label": 0, "content": "Hello. Wisdom teeth or third molars are usually the last ones to erupt. During the eruption time, there are some inflammation and redness in gum pad known as pericoronitis. If the orientation of the tooth is not in a proper path, the dentist decides to extract it. This is a universally accepted method because there is no sufficient space in the jaw for the tooth to come out. If the tooth was left as it is, it can cause more problems in the future. So I suggest you go for extraction. This is the best way to cure your problem, do not be panic because the whole procedure will be performed under local anesthesia."}, {"label": 1, "content": "It is possible that swelling due to wisdom tooth eruption can be managed with measures such as warm salt water rinses and over-the-counter pain medication, but in most cases, extraction is the most effective way to manage the problem. If the wisdom tooth is causing discomfort or is coming in at an angle that is causing pain or affecting your other teeth, extraction is likely the best course of action. If you are concerned about the extraction process, it is important to discuss your concerns with your dentist or oral surgeon so that they can address your concerns and help you feel more comfortable. They may be able to offer options such as sedation or pain management to make the procedure more comfortable for you."}, {"label": 0, "content": "Hi.... I understand your concern. As the kid otherwise normal I feel that it could be because of intense cough that he has this blood streaks in the sputum. But if there is any family history of tuberculosis contact then definitely this required for the evaluation.I suggest that you get him checked by his pediatrician once.Regards - Dr. Sumanth"}, {"label": 1, "content": "It's always a good idea to be cautious when someone is experiencing coughing up blood and vomiting, as these can be signs of a more serious condition. It's important to have your child evaluated by a healthcare professional as soon as possible to determine the cause of the symptoms and appropriate treatment.\n\nThere are several possible causes for coughing up blood and vomiting, including pneumonia, bronchitis, asthma, and lung cancer. It's also possible that your child may have an infection or inflammation in the respiratory tract or gastrointestinal system. It's important to have a healthcare professional evaluate your child to determine the cause of the symptoms and provide appropriate treatment.\n\nIn the meantime, it's important to encourage your child to drink fluids to stay hydrated and to rest. You can also try using a humidifier in your child's room to help loosen and clear any mucus from the respiratory tract. It's also important to keep your child away from tobacco smoke, as it can irritate the respiratory tract and make symptoms worse.\n\nAgain, it's important to have your child evaluated by a healthcare professional as soon as possible to determine the cause of the symptoms and get the appropriate treatment."}, {"label": 0, "content": "Hello, Yes, faster heart rate, it persists for a long time like over years, can cause myocardial fatigue which ultimately results in tachycardia-induced cardiomyopathy. Yes, some patients if taken care properly with medication and precautions do improve up to some extent but 100% recovery is not very common. Hope I have answered your query. Let me know if I can assist you further. Regards,Dr. Bhanu Partap,Cardiologist"}, {"label": 1, "content": "Rapid heart rate, or tachycardia, can potentially cause damage to the heart if it is sustained for a long period of time. Wolfe-Parkinson-White syndrome is a condition that can cause episodes of tachycardia, and it is possible that the rapid heart rate your husband experienced in May could have contributed to any damage to his heart.\n\nIt is important for your husband to follow the treatment plan recommended by his healthcare provider in order to manage his Wolfe-Parkinson-White syndrome and minimize the risk of further damage to his heart. This may include medications, lifestyle changes, and possibly additional surgery.\n\nIt is also important for your husband to follow a healthy lifestyle, including eating a healthy diet, getting regular exercise, and avoiding smoking and excessive alcohol consumption. These measures can help to improve heart health and reduce the risk of further damage to the heart.\n\nIt is not uncommon for people with Wolfe-Parkinson-White syndrome to experience additional episodes of tachycardia, so it is important for your husband to be aware of the signs and symptoms and to seek medical attention if necessary. Other potential complications of Wolfe-Parkinson-White syndrome can include heart failure and abnormal heart rhythms, so it is important for your husband to continue to receive regular medical care to monitor for these issues."}, {"label": 0, "content": "Hi...by what you quote I think that it could be a simple viral exanthem or it could be hand foot mouth disease. Whatever it is  I suggest you show her to her regular pediatricaina and get the opinion to be on the safer side.Hope my answer was helpful for you.  I am happy to help any time. Further clarifications and consultations on Health care magic are welcome. If you do not have any clarifications, you can close the discussion and rate the answer. Wish your kid good health.Dr. Sumanth MBBS., DCH., DNB (Paed).,"}, {"label": 1, "content": "It's difficult to diagnose a medical condition without examining the patient and obtaining more information. However, red spots on the soles of the feet can be caused by a variety of factors, including infections, allergies, or underlying medical conditions. It's important to bring your child to a doctor for an evaluation if you are concerned about their health.\n\nIn the meantime, it's important to monitor your child's symptoms and pay attention to any changes. It's also important to ensure that your child is getting enough fluids, as increased urination and decreased appetite can be signs of dehydration. If your child is not drinking enough fluids or if you notice any other concerning symptoms, such as lethargy or fever, it's important to contact your child's doctor for further advice."}, {"label": 0, "content": "Dear friend.Thanks for sharing your concern.Excessive usage of xylocaine is not recommended,please remember your tooth is already infected so the swelling is due to that,and excessive usage of anesthetic spray has added on to this phenomenon.It can effect locally but your toothache is due to deep pulpal infection,which requires treatment.you can confirm it through x ray.you are advised to visit your dentist soon and start with antibiotics and analgesics for reducing pain and infection.Meanwhile please stop using xylocaine ,If required,you can take analgesics till you visit your dentist.swelling will reduce only after appropriate treatment, probably root canal.Warm saline rinses will help relieve oral infection.Hope it helps.Thanks.Take care."}, {"label": 1, "content": "I'm sorry to hear about the discomfort you are experiencing. It's important to seek medical attention if you are experiencing any unusual or concerning symptoms after using a medication. Xylocaine is a local anesthetic that is used to numb a specific area of the body. It is not uncommon for the area where the medication was applied to feel numb or swollen for a short period of time after use. However, if the swelling or pain persists or increases, it is important to seek medical attention as soon as possible.\n\nIn the meantime, you can try using a cold compress or ice pack on the affected area to help reduce swelling and numbness. Avoid eating or drinking hot foods or liquids and try to keep the affected area as still as possible to minimize discomfort.\n\nIt is important to follow the instructions for use provided with the medication and to only use the medication as directed. If you have any questions or concerns about the use of Xylocaine, you should speak with a healthcare provider. They will be able to provide you with more specific advice and guidance based on your individual circumstances."}, {"label": 0, "content": "Hello,I think you should check your blood pressure and blood sugar too. Low blood sugar can cause these symptoms and if you are a diabetic taking medication or insulin can be causing this. It doesn't seem related to thyroid issues.Hope I have answered your question. Let me know if I can assist you further. Regards,Dr. Olgeta Xhufka, General & Family Physician"}, {"label": 1, "content": "Dizziness and blurred vision are not common side effects of thyroxine, which is a medication used to treat an underactive thyroid gland. Low blood pressure can sometimes cause dizziness and blurred vision, but it is not the only possible cause. There are many other potential causes of these symptoms, including issues with blood sugar levels, inner ear problems, and certain medications.\n\nIt is important to discuss any new or unusual symptoms with your healthcare provider. They will be able to help you determine the cause and recommend appropriate treatment. In the meantime, it is important to be cautious when driving or engaging in activities that require alertness and coordination, as dizziness and blurred vision can affect your ability to safely perform these tasks."}, {"label": 0, "content": "**1. Ciplatrim [ sibutramine hydrochloride monohydrate] is indicated for the management of obesity, including weight loss as well as maintenance of weight loss, but 'depression' being one of the ADR [adverse drug reaction] of the drug limited it use in associated depressio