rritation that occurs when the skin comes into contact with certain substances. This can be triggered by things like makeup, skincare products, and fabrics, as well as by irritants like pollutants and chemicals. If you suspect that your red, itchy spots may be caused by contact dermatitis, you may want to try avoiding the substances that seem to trigger your symptoms and using a hypoallergenic moisturizer to help soothe your skin. Over-the-counter hydrocortisone cream may also be helpful in reducing inflammation and itching.\n\nAnother potential cause of red, itchy spots on the face is seborrheic dermatitis, which is a condition that causes a red, scaly rash on the face, scalp, and other areas of the body. It is often accompanied by itching and can be triggered by a variety of factors, including hormonal changes, stress, and certain medications. If you think you may have seborrheic dermatitis, you may want to try using an over-the-counter antifungal cream or shampoo to help control the condition.\n\nIf your red, itchy spots do not improve with self-care measures, or if you are experiencing other symptoms such as fever, difficulty breathing, or swelling, it's important to see a healthcare provider for proper diagnosis and treatment. They will be able to determine the cause of your symptoms and recommend appropriate treatment options."}, {"label": 0, "content": "Hello. I reviewed your history. A stye is because of bacterial infection of glands if eyelids. Since this is infection WBC count is expected yo increase. WBC count in your cade is within normal limits, up to 11,000 is normal, no need to worry. The recurrence is because if recurrence of infection and recurrences occur in people with risk factors like blepharitis, exposure to dust. Hence consult your eye doctor to find out the underlying cause and treatment accordingly. As of now, you need to use antibiotic eye ointment and hot compression."}, {"label": 1, "content": "A stye is a type of infection that occurs in the oil glands of the eyelid. While an increase in white blood cell (WBC) count can be a sign of infection, it is not necessarily the cause of a stye. There are other factors that can contribute to the development of a stye, such as poor hygiene, a weakened immune system, or underlying medical conditions.\n\nIt is important to see a healthcare provider for proper diagnosis and treatment of a stye. The provider may recommend warm compresses, cleaning the affected area with an antibacterial solution, or prescribing antibiotic eye drops or ointment to help clear the infection. In some cases, the stye may need to be drained surgically.\n\nIt is also important to practice good hygiene, such as washing your hands frequently and avoiding sharing towels or makeup, to help prevent the spread of infection. If you have a reoccurring stye or are experiencing any other eye-related symptoms, it is important to see a healthcare provider for further evaluation and treatment."}, {"label": 0, "content": "Hello! Thanks for putting your query in HCM. I am a Gastroenterologist (DM). Acetoaminophen is rather safe until it is taken in safe dose that is less than 4 gm per day. Ibuprophen is rather unsafe as it can cause hepatitis. For pain you can take tramadol also which is safe for you. Avoid alcohol, any drug which is hepatotoxic. get vaccination for hepatitis B and A. avoid high fat diet. DO regular exercise. Take lots of fruits and vegetables as they are rich in antioxidantsI hope I have answered your query and this will help you. If you have any further query  I will be happy to answer that too. Remain in touch and get-well soon."}, {"label": 1, "content": "There are several options for pain relief in people with hepatitis C, including non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drugs (NSAIDs) such as ibuprofen and naproxen, as well as acetaminophen (also known as paracetamol). It is important to follow the recommendations of your healthcare provider when it comes to taking medications, as certain medications may be contraindicated or may need to be used with caution in people with hepatitis C.\n\nIbuprofen is a type of NSAID that is commonly used for pain relief and fever reduction. Motrin is the brand name for ibuprofen.\n\nOther options for pain relief in people with hepatitis C may include prescription pain medications, such as opioids or other medications that work in different ways to reduce pain. These medications should be used with caution and under the supervision of a healthcare provider, as they can have potential side effects and may carry risks of addiction or overdose.\n\nIt is also important to consider non-pharmacological approaches to pain management, such as physical therapy, exercise, heat or cold therapy, and relaxation techniques. These approaches may be helpful in reducing pain and improving function, and may be used in combination with medication.\n\nIt is always a good idea to talk to your healthcare provider about the best options for pain relief and fever reduction for your specific situation. They can help you determine the most appropriate treatment plan for your needs, taking into account your medical history, current medications, and other factors."}, {"label": 0, "content": "Hi,     Gel like substance in stool is mucus.It indicates intestinal infection.     you might have caught it by contaminated water or food.         Take tab.Dependal M twice a day for acouple of days.Drink boiled water,light diet.----If you are not well within two days-- pl. get your stools examined . it will reveil the organism responsible. A course of proper medicines will be sufficientThanks."}, {"label": 1, "content": "There are several possible causes of gel-like substance in the stool. Some common causes include:\n\nFatty stools: If you have a high-fat diet or are experiencing malabsorption (inability to absorb nutrients from food), your stools may be more oily and appear more gel-like.\n\nInflammatory bowel disease (IBD): IBD, such as Crohn's disease or ulcerative colitis, can cause inflammation in the digestive tract, leading to gel-like stools.\n\nIrritable bowel syndrome (IBS): IBS is a common digestive disorder that can cause a range of symptoms, including diarrhea, constipation, and gel-like stools.\n\nInfections: Infections, such as bacterial gastroenteritis or parasites, can cause changes in the consistency of the stool.\n\nIf you are experiencing gel-like stools and are concerned, it is important to speak to a healthcare provider for proper evaluation and treatment. They will be able to determine the cause of the gel-like stools and recommend the appropriate treatment."}, {"label": 0, "content": "Greetings !Well it seems like you are suffering from Depression and anxiety which have taken a toll on your personal and social life and also possibly on your professional life which can be summed up by saying that these two conditions have caused what is called as functional impairment and taken away your quality of life.Now this can be managed by a combination of Drug therapy and Counseling.Drug therapy shall include an anti depressant drug such as escitalopram at dose of 10-20 mg / day and an anti anxiety drug such as clonazepam at dose of 0.25 mg twice a day. While this drug therapy will manage your symptoms for now but for the long run and for future prevention of such a predicament you need to seek counseling in the form of CBT ( Cognitive Behavior Therapy) which is a special counseling technique that teaches a person coping skills and strategies to endure and manage stressful life situations.I hope this helps.Regards"}, {"label": 1, "content": "I'm sorry to hear that you're struggling with anxiety and feeling like the whole world is against you. It's important to remember that you're not alone in this and that there are many people who have experienced similar feelings. There are many things you can try to help overcome anxiety and improve your mental health. Here are a few suggestions:\n\nSeek professional help: It can be helpful to talk to a mental health professional, such as a therapist or counselor, about your anxiety and how it's affecting your life. They can help you develop coping strategies and work through any underlying issues that may be contributing to your anxiety.\n\nPractice relaxation techniques: Techniques such as deep breathing, progressive muscle relaxation, and meditation can help calm your mind and body.\n\nGet regular exercise: Exercise can help reduce anxiety and improve overall mental health. Aim for at least 30 minutes of moderate-intensity exercise, such as brisk walking or cycling, most days of the week.\n\nEat a healthy diet: Eating a well-balanced diet that includes plenty of fruits, vegetables, and whole grains can help improve your mood and reduce anxiety.\n\nConnect with others: It's important to have a supportive network of people you can turn to when you're feeling anxious or down. Make an effort to spend time with friends and loved ones, and consider joining a support group or online community where you can connect with others who are dealing with similar issues.\n\nFind activities that you enjoy: Doing things you enjoy, whether it's hobbies or spending time with loved ones, can help take your mind off your anxiety and improve your mood.\n\nTake breaks and practice self-care: Make sure to set aside time for relaxation and self-care, such as getting enough sleep, taking breaks from technology, and finding ways to reduce stress.\n\nIt's important to remember that overcoming anxiety takes time and effort, and it may not happen overnight. Be patient with yourself and try to focus on the progress you've made, even if it's small. If you continue to struggle, don't hesitate to reach out for additional support."}, {"label": 0, "content": "Hi I admire you for positive outlook.It is due to social anxiety.Cheeks shivering while conversation is the feature of anxiety.Best way to handle this is exposure therapy.Expose your self as much as