the uterus, can cause abdominal pain, bleeding, and back pain.\n\nMiscarriage: Abdominal pain, bleeding, and back pain can be symptoms of a miscarriage, which is the loss of a pregnancy before the 20th week.\n\nKidney stones: Kidney stones can cause abdominal pain and back pain, as well as blood in the urine.\n\nIt is important to seek medical attention if you are experiencing these symptoms, as some of the conditions listed above can be serious if not treated promptly. Your healthcare provider will be able to determine the cause of your symptoms and recommend the appropriate treatment."}, {"label": 0, "content": "Hi,It is either muscle pain or costochondritis. Take ibuprofen 400 mg, if pain continues, then take it twice a day for 3-5 days.Don't worry, there is nothing serious.Take careCome back if you have any further questions"}, {"label": 1, "content": "Chest pain can be caused by a variety of conditions, some of which can be serious. It's important to get a proper evaluation by a healthcare professional if you are experiencing chest pain, particularly if it is accompanied by other symptoms such as shortness of breath, nausea, or sweating.\n\nThere are many possible causes of left-sided chest pain, including:\n\nMusculoskeletal problems: Chest pain on the left side could be caused by muscle strain, a pinched nerve, or other musculoskeletal issues.\n\nHeart problems: Chest pain on the left side could be a sign of a heart attack, angina (chest pain caused by reduced blood flow to the heart), or other heart problems.\n\nLung problems: Chest pain on the left side could be caused by a lung infection, such as pneumonia, or by other lung problems such as asthma or chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD).\n\nGastrointestinal problems: Chest pain on the left side could be caused by gastrointestinal issues such as acid reflux (heartburn) or a peptic ulcer.\n\nOther causes: There are many other possible causes of left-sided chest pain, including an injury to the chest, a blood clot in the lung (pulmonary embolism), and even anxiety or stress.\n\nIt's important to see a healthcare professional for an evaluation if you are experiencing chest pain, particularly if it is accompanied by other symptoms or if it is severe or persistent. They will be able to determine the cause of your symptoms and recommend the appropriate treatment."}, {"label": 0, "content": "I think this excessive sweating and tension are part of Anxiety neurosis. It is a common problem. Try to calm done by incorporating yoga, meditation,exercises in your daily routine. You can try benzodiazepines like clonazepam after consultation with a family physician or psychiatrist. You vitals and proper history will rule out  an secondary cause of your symptoms."}, {"label": 1, "content": "I'm sorry to hear that you are experiencing nerve problems. It is important to speak with a medical professional to determine the cause of your symptoms and the best course of treatment.\n\nThere are several potential causes of nerve problems, including neurological disorders, infections, injuries, and certain medications. In order to determine the cause of your symptoms, a medical professional will likely ask you about your medical history and conduct a physical examination. They may also order tests such as an electromyogram (EMG) or nerve conduction study to assess the function of your nerves.\n\nTreatment for nerve problems may include medications, physical therapy, surgery, or other interventions, depending on the cause and severity of the problem. It is important to follow your healthcare provider's treatment recommendations in order to manage your symptoms and improve your quality of life.\n\nIf you are experiencing nerve problems, I recommend speaking with a medical professional for a proper diagnosis and treatment plan."}, {"label": 0, "content": "HiWelcome to the HCMThere is no need to be worried about 3-5 pus cells on urine examination. It needs no treatment unless and until a child is symptomatic. I would recommend you to go for urine culture and sensitivity report before starting antibiotics as it is a more definitive test for urinary tract infections. As such, most common reason for fever in this age is self limiting viral infections which need just symptomatic treatment like acetaminophen for fever. Hopefully this will help you. I would be glad to help you for any further child health related query.Take care"}, {"label": 1, "content": "It's not normal for a child to have pus cells in their urine, and an elevated level of pus cells (also known as pyuria) can indicate the presence of a urinary tract infection (UTI). UTIs are fairly common in young children, especially girls, and can be treated with antibiotics. It's important to follow your doctor's recommendations and complete the full course of antibiotics as prescribed to ensure that the infection is fully cleared.\n\nIf your child is experiencing fever, it's important to monitor their temperature and ensure that they are getting enough fluids. It's also a good idea to wash your hands frequently and encourage your child to drink plenty of fluids to help flush bacteria out of the urinary tract and prevent further infections.\n\nIn addition to treatment with antibiotics, your child's doctor may also recommend follow-up testing to ensure that the infection has been fully resolved and to check for any underlying causes that may have contributed to the development of the UTI. If your child continues to have recurrent UTIs, further evaluation may be necessary to determine the cause and determine the best course of treatment."}, {"label": 0, "content": "Hi. I have gone through the child's history and reports (attachment removed to protect patient identity). For further information consult a paediatrician online -->https://www.icliniq.com/ask-a-doctor-online/paediatrician"}, {"label": 1, "content": "beyonddcdcdcdc@163.com\nQ. What will be your treatment plan for a 3 months old with inguinal hernia?Hi doctor,My colleague\u2019s son, who is 3 months old, has been diagnosed with an inguinal hernia on the right groin. Hence, I would appreciate your feedback and let us know if a surgery is immediately required or not. If the surgery is not required urgently, please advise when this would be required. I have enclosed all the medical and scan reports for your kind reference.\nInguinal hernias in infants are usually treated with surgery. The timing of the surgery will depend on the size and location of the hernia and the presence of any symptoms. In general, it is recommended to repair inguinal hernias in infants as soon as possible to prevent complications such as incarceration or strangulation, in which the hernia becomes stuck and the blood supply to the trapped intestine is cut off. However, it is important to consult with a pediatric surgeon to determine the best course of treatment for your colleague's son. The surgeon will consider the specific characteristics of the hernia and the overall health and medical history of the child in order to determine the most appropriate treatment plan."}, {"label": 0, "content": "Hi ThereNo it's totally fine there's nothing to be concerned. The normal recommended range of Blood pressure for an adult is upto 140 systolic and 90 diastolic. Your Bp is well within the recommended limits and you are also on a good exercise schedule. So nothing to worry about just maintain your healthy lifestyle habits.I wish you good health"}, {"label": 1, "content": "It is generally considered normal for blood pressure to be slightly higher in people who engage in regular physical activity, as their hearts are stronger and more efficient at pumping blood. However, it is important to have your blood pressure checked by a healthcare provider to determine whether it is within a healthy range for you. It is especially important to have your blood pressure checked if you are experiencing any symptoms that could be related to high blood pressure, such as headache, dizziness, shortness of breath, or chest pain. It is also a good idea to see a healthcare provider regularly for check-ups, even if you are feeling well. This can help to identify any potential health issues early on and allow for prompt treatment if necessary."}, {"label": 0, "content": "hi dear,what kind of shock you have with your boy friend?since when you have such complain?with other friends and family member you have any problem related to emotion or not?is there any other associated symptoms?consult psychiatrist for detail history and counselling.Thank you"}, {"label": 1, "content": "It's normal to have ups and downs in relationships, and it's possible that you're going through a tough time with your boyfriend right now. It's also possible that you may be experiencing some form of depression or emotional numbness, which can cause a lack of emotional feelings. It's important to try to identify any underlying issues that may be contributing to these feelings and to seek support if needed.\n\nThere are a few things you can try to help address these feelings:\n\nTalk to a therapist or counselor about your feelings. A mental health professional can help you explore the root causes of your emotional numbness and develop coping strategies.\n\nPractice self-care. Taking care of yourself physically, mentally, and emotionally can help improve your overall well-being and may help you feel more connected to your emotions.\n\nTry to reconnect with your feelings. It can be helpful to spend time alone, journaling, or doing activities that allow you to tap into your emotions.\n\nTake breaks from the relationship. It's okay to take some time for yourself if you need it. Taking breaks can help you recharge and gain perspective, which can be helpful in improving your emotional connection with your boyfriend.\n\nIt's important to remember that these feelings are temporary and that you can work through them with the right support and self-care practices. If you continue to feel emotionally numb or if these feelings are causing significant distress in your life, it's important to seek professional help."}, {"label": 0, "content": "Hello, Infective causes like urethritis or urinary tract infection must be ruled out. A urine culture is required to look for any signs of infection. If there is any fractures of infection, antibiotics must be started. Nothing much to worry as most of the cases respond well to antibiotics. Hope I have answered your query. Let me know if I can assist you further. Take care Regards,Dr. Shinas Hussain"}, {"label": 1, "content": "Stinging while urinating after masturbation can be caused by a number of things, including irritation or inflammation of the urethra (the tube that carries urine out of the body) or a urinary tract infection (UTI). UTIs are more common in women than in men, but they can affect anyone. UTIs can be caused by bacteria entering the urinary tract, and they can cause symptoms such as pain or burning while urinating, frequent urges to urinate, and blood in the urine.\n\nDrinking plenty of water and cranberry juice can help flush out bacteria and may help reduce the symptoms of a UTI. It's also important to practice good hygiene, including washing your hands before and after masturbating and cleaning the area around your genitals thoroughly. Avoid using harsh soaps or chemicals on your genitals, and wear loose, breathable clothing to allow for proper ventilation.\n\nIf the stinging persists or if you have other symptoms such as fever or back pain, it's important to see a healthcare provider for proper diagnosis and treatment. UTIs can be treated with antibiotics, and it's important to finish the full course of treatment to ensure that the infection is completely cleared."}, {"label": 0, "content": "hithanks for using hcm. my congratulations to you for being future mother by gods grace16th week of pregnancy normally the first time pregnant mother feels the movement of the baby called q