nclude obesity, high levels of triglycerides in the blood, high alcohol consumption, and rapid weight loss.\n\nThere are several medications that may be used to treat fatty liver, including:\n\nUdiliv 300 (ursodeoxycholic acid): This medication helps to dissolve cholesterol in the liver and is often used to treat fatty liver caused by high cholesterol or high levels of triglycerides in the blood.\n\nRose day 10mg (rosiglitazone): This medication is used to treat type 2 diabetes and may be effective in reducing the amount of fat in the liver.\n\nFebutaz 40 (febuxostat): This medication is used to treat high levels of uric acid in the blood and may be effective in reducing the amount of fat in the liver.\n\nOther medications that may be used to treat fatty liver include statins, which are used to lower cholesterol levels, and vitamin E, which has been shown to be effective in reducing the amount of fat in the liver in some studies.\n\nIf you are working in a foreign country and are concerned about your fatty liver, it is important to speak with a healthcare provider about your options for treatment. They can help you determine the best course of action based on the underlying cause of your fatty liver and your overall health. It is also important to follow a healthy lifestyle, including maintaining a healthy weight, exercising regularly, and following a healthy diet to help manage your fatty liver and improve your overall health."}, {"label": 0, "content": "HelloThanks for your query,based on the facts that you have posted it appears that you have developed red patches and swelling of foreskin and glans after unprotected sex .This is most likely to be due to infection of foreskin and glans (Ballano-Posthatitis).However in view of having unprotected sex possibility of STD has to be ruled out.Please get basic screening test for STD done to be rest assured about free from acquiring STD.You need to take broad spectrum antibiotic like Cefexine along with anti inflammatory 