ogist... hope it helps.. tc"}, {"label": 1, "content": "It is generally safe to undergo an MRI after orthognathic surgery, regardless of the type of metal used in the procedure. Titanium is a commonly used material for surgical implants, including in orthognathic surgery, and it is generally considered safe for MRI. However, it is important to inform the MRI technologist and the radiologist about any previous surgery that involved the placement of metal implants or foreign bodies. This information will be included in the MRI safety screening questionnaire and will help the healthcare team determine the most appropriate MRI protocol for you.\n\nTo determine the type of metal used in your previous orthognathic surgery, you can try contacting the hospital or clinic where the surgery was performed and asking for a copy of your medical records. Your records should include information about the materials used during the surgery, including the type of metal used for the plates and screws. You can also ask your surgeon or another healthcare provider who was involved in your surgery for this information.\n\nIf you are unable to obtain this information or if you have concerns about the safety of the MRI, you can discuss your options with the MRI technologist, the radiologist, or your primary care provider. They can help you determine the best course of action based on your individual situation."}, {"label": 0, "content": "Hi and welcome to HCM. Thanks for the query. It may or may not be related to his injury but he should do ct scan of head to rule out some more serious diagnoses. if there is no relation with injury he should anyways do more detiled neurolgoic work up.Wish you good health. Regards"}, {"label": 1, "content": "!\nToo many requests in 1 hour. Try again later.\n\n\n\nThere was an error generating a response"}, {"label": 0, "content": "hi. based on the description of your symptoms it appears to be radiation induced sides effect.  you need to modify your dietary ha